Deciding between joining tables and blending data:
Summary:
To decide whether to join a table or blend data, consider the number of connections in your workbook, how the data is related, the number of records/flows, and the type of views needed.
Traditional table joins are usually the best choice as the work is done by the database itself, cross-database joins are recommended over data blending due to fewer limitations, and data blending should be used when there is a large amount of data in the secondary table.
Table joins are better for one-to-one relationships while one-to-many or many-to-many relationships can cause duplicated data and performance issues.
Data blending only supports left joins and is more flexible for quickly changing linking properties but should be avoided on dimensions with many unique values.
To efficiently combine data sources, limit the number of tables and create a separate data source for each analytical scenario. Avoid blending data on dimensions with many unique values.



